00:32:29.080 --> 00:32:31.620
Okay, so I wanted to take you
through the lyrics, of course,

00:32:31.620 --> 00:32:34.390
because they are very
hard to understand.

00:32:34.390 --> 00:32:39.090
He is obviously not a
native speaker of English,

00:32:39.090 --> 00:32:41.860
and he also didn't have
English at school, right.

00:32:41.860 --> 00:32:43.160
He had to take Russian.

00:32:43.160 --> 00:32:47.830
And then, if you took English,
the contact hours that you had

00:32:47.830 --> 00:32:49.630
with English were very, very few.

00:32:49.630 --> 00:32:53.110
So what he usually did, he learned
English from record sleeves,

00:32:53.110 --> 00:32:56.680
of course, from the covers of
LPs, and then also he had friends

00:32:56.680 --> 00:33:00.340
from the Technical University in
Dresden who were native Britons,

00:33:00.340 --> 00:33:05.180
and they were lectures for the
University and taught English.

00:33:05.180 --> 00:33:08.980
And he kind of wrote his text
in German and translated them

00:33:08.980 --> 00:33:12.030
into English and then kind of
polished them and gave them

00:33:12.030 --> 00:33:14.840
to his friends and they
said, this is English enough,

00:33:14.840 --> 00:33:16.530
or this is not English
enough [laughter].

00:33:16.530 --> 00:33:19.490
So this is how it happened.

00:33:19.490 --> 00:33:23.290
And you can see the
gestures of boasting, right.

00:33:23.290 --> 00:33:27.230
I'm the best, I'm the greatest.

00:33:27.230 --> 00:33:33.240
And he's I think music history,
so he doesn't really identify

00:33:33.240 --> 00:33:36.390
with anything of the
German musical tradition.

00:33:36.390 --> 00:33:40.450
He has his posse, right,
who was running this town,

00:33:40.450 --> 00:33:44.520
not the mayor of Dresden, it
was he and his posse, right.

00:33:44.520 --> 00:33:46.900
[laughter] And so [inaudible]
everybody else,

00:33:46.900 --> 00:33:50.760
and especially the
compromised money musician.

00:33:50.760 --> 00:33:55.940 position:56%
So compromise is basically or refers
to the compromise that you had

00:33:55.940 --> 00:34:02.450 position:56%
to kind of deal with when you wanted
to make music, to perform in front

00:34:02.450 --> 00:34:04.610
of this commission
that would assess you

00:34:04.610 --> 00:34:06.370
and then hand out these licenses.

00:34:06.370 --> 00:34:14.810 position:56%
And usually, money musicians kind of
self-censored in order to do that.

00:34:14.810 --> 00:34:17.700
So they said, okay, we're not going
to speak up against the state,

00:34:17.700 --> 00:34:21.440
we're not going to have too
much guitars, or we're not going

00:34:21.440 --> 00:34:23.350
to have this line in there.

00:34:23.350 --> 00:34:27.340
But we're very conformist, and
this gives us a chance at least

00:34:27.340 --> 00:34:30.700
to make music and to perform.

00:34:30.700 --> 00:34:32.710
And that's something he criticizes.

00:34:32.710 --> 00:34:34.450
Although he has a license too.

00:34:34.450 --> 00:34:38.370
But the way he did it was,
since nobody spoke English

00:34:38.370 --> 00:34:41.070
in these assessments commissions.

00:34:41.070 --> 00:34:44.810
He handed them the German
translations, and in the space

00:34:44.810 --> 00:34:47.980
between the German and the
English, he could kind of slip

00:34:47.980 --> 00:34:52.500
in conformist German lines and
not conformist English lines.

00:34:52.500 --> 00:34:54.470
So that's how he did it.

00:34:54.470 --> 00:34:57.630
And that's why he could call
everybody else money musicians,

00:34:57.630 --> 00:35:00.880
because they only did it for the
money, but he did it for a cause.

00:35:00.880 --> 00:35:05.710
And the craftsman vision
is how to do it the right,

00:35:05.710 --> 00:35:12.750
how to play music well, but
it's without a soul for him.

00:35:12.750 --> 00:35:18.030
So his soul is hurt when he
listens to this kind of stuff.

00:35:18.030 --> 00:35:20.020
And he's also dissing
everybody else, right,

00:35:20.020 --> 00:35:22.440
the compromised money
musicians running zigzag,

00:35:22.440 --> 00:35:24.120
following the party line.

00:35:24.120 --> 00:35:27.550
And then so he doesn't need it.

00:35:27.550 --> 00:35:33.490
And he also is dissing them by
calling them with weaker melodies,

00:35:33.490 --> 00:35:35.930
and he's, and this
is my favorite line,

00:35:35.930 --> 00:35:41.060
we're laughing watching the
pointer of our soccer seeker.

00:35:41.060 --> 00:35:46.090
The German original is or I
translate into better English now,

00:35:46.090 --> 00:35:47.960
and please excuse my language.

00:35:47.960 --> 00:35:53.030
We're laughing watching the pointer
of our mother fuckers, right.

00:35:53.030 --> 00:35:57.380
So I said it before, excuse
my language [laughter].

00:35:57.380 --> 00:36:03.660
So [inaudible] result of
this pig meat nation is

00:36:03.660 --> 00:36:06.060
because the GDR was very proud

00:36:06.060 --> 00:36:10.440
that it fed everybody
and it did so with pork.

00:36:10.440 --> 00:36:14.100
So this is why he calls
it pig meat nation.

00:36:15.300 --> 00:36:22.770
And he hates the cultural
functionaries, which he calls --

00:36:22.770 --> 00:36:26.960
well, the people who
were responsible

00:36:26.960 --> 00:36:30.550 position:56%
for the socialist cultural landscape
are always on vacation it seems,

00:36:30.550 --> 00:36:33.870
and that's why nothing
really good can ever happen.

00:36:33.870 --> 00:36:35.170
And they're also suckers.

00:36:35.170 --> 00:36:40.870
And in this void, he appears and
he brings kind of more culture,

00:36:40.870 --> 00:36:44.510
and everybody else
better stay behind him,

00:36:44.510 --> 00:36:48.720 position:56%
because he brings more entertainment
and good times and also criticism.

00:36:48.720 --> 00:36:51.160
So that's what he does.

00:36:51.160 --> 00:36:53.860
I admit that I'm sure
that not everybody

00:36:53.860 --> 00:36:56.840
in his audience always
understood him [laughter],

00:36:56.840 --> 00:36:59.000
at least not in the
Palace of the Republic.

00:36:59.000 --> 00:37:03.080
But he had every fortnight he
had big parties in Dresden,

00:37:03.080 --> 00:37:07.960
and he had like an
audience, he had regulars.

00:37:07.960 --> 00:37:11.250
And I'm pretty sure that
those people knew what he was

00:37:11.250 --> 00:37:12.550
talking about.

00:37:12.550 --> 00:37:15.810
And also he had regular
workshops where he invited people

00:37:15.810 --> 00:37:19.460
to share their lyrics, to
help them with rhyming,

00:37:19.460 --> 00:37:24.150
with the craft making beats,
and so on and so forth.

00:37:24.150 --> 00:37:27.790
So I guess that he had he could
reach out to this community

00:37:27.790 --> 00:37:32.150
of hip-hoppers, and
excluding the adult world

00:37:32.150 --> 00:37:35.430
who was keen on monitoring him.

00:37:35.430 --> 00:37:38.790
All right, to conclude,
from 1983 to 1990,

00:37:38.790 --> 00:37:40.620
hip-hop culture became
very much alive

00:37:40.620 --> 00:37:42.680
in the German Democratic Republic.

00:37:42.680 --> 00:37:46.810
A small but highly visible scene
gives the authorities positive

00:37:46.810 --> 00:37:50.830 position:56%
disposition towards African-American
culture as working-class culture,

00:37:50.830 --> 00:37:52.940
and created its own
versions of breakdance,

00:37:52.940 --> 00:37:55.250
graffiti, Djing, and rap.

00:37:55.250 --> 00:37:57.790
In this process of
cultural transfer,

00:37:57.790 --> 00:37:59.900
"Beat Street" played
a decisive role.

00:37:59.900 --> 00:38:03.350
Originally imported in order to
educate good young socialists

00:38:03.350 --> 00:38:07.140
about bad capitalism in America,
it had quite the opposite effect,

00:38:07.140 --> 00:38:09.940
and instilled in many
young viewers the wish

00:38:09.940 --> 00:38:12.400
to become a hip-hopper
in New York City.

00:38:12.400 --> 00:38:15.750
At the same time, it served as
a role model for aspiring B-Boys

00:38:15.750 --> 00:38:19.260
and B-Girls, graffiti
writers, and DJs, and rappers,

00:38:19.260 --> 00:38:23.310
to emulate what they
saw on the movie screen.

00:38:23.310 --> 00:38:26.070
Against their performances,
be it on official stages,

00:38:26.070 --> 00:38:27.370
be it on the streets,

00:38:27.370 --> 00:38:32.470
the controlling agency strategies
proved useless in the long run.

00:38:32.470 --> 00:38:36.620
The fall of Iron Curtain also meant
a last curtain for hip-hop culture

00:38:36.620 --> 00:38:39.190
in the GDR, at least for a while.

00:38:39.190 --> 00:38:42.020
Apart from the new challenges
that came with having to adjust

00:38:42.020 --> 00:38:44.990
to a new political system,
hip-hoppers had to cope

00:38:44.990 --> 00:38:47.000
with the collapse of
socialist landscape

00:38:47.000 --> 00:38:49.550
that had promoted and
fostered hip-hop.

00:38:49.550 --> 00:38:52.370
Although it had done so with the
intention to control and steer it

00:38:52.370 --> 00:38:56.920
into the right direction,
acrobatic folk dance, right,

00:38:56.920 --> 00:39:00.530
many B-Boy crews had profited
from the money, opportunities,

00:39:00.530 --> 00:39:03.400
and perks that this
arrangement had included,

00:39:03.400 --> 00:39:07.030
such as free practice
space, etcetera.

00:39:07.030 --> 00:39:10.020
Now that it was gone and other
things were more important,

00:39:10.020 --> 00:39:13.130
many hip-hoppers took
a hiatus from hip-hop.

00:39:13.130 --> 00:39:15.790
However, in the early '90s,
they found back together,

00:39:15.790 --> 00:39:19.240
often in concert with
peers from the West.

00:39:19.240 --> 00:39:23.100
And in East-Western collaborations,
they founded new crews who danced,

00:39:23.100 --> 00:39:25.990
rapped, spray-painted
graffiti, and made music.

00:39:25.990 --> 00:39:29.630
Thus, they contributed to the
process of reunifying Germany

00:39:29.630 --> 00:39:32.020
after 1990, but that's
another chapter

00:39:32.020 --> 00:39:33.330
that I haven't researched yet.

00:39:33.330 --> 00:39:35.510
So thank you very much
for your attention.

00:39:35.510 --> 00:39:47.040
